    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, so it's basically about who pays if there's a lawsuit. but in this contract, it says i have to indemnify them against any \"third-party claims of infringement.\" what does that actually look like in real life? like what kind of thing would trigger that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A third-party claim of infringement, in real life, means someone else—a third party—sues *them* because you did something that stepped on their toes, usually by using something they own, like a design, a piece of code, or a trademark. If you're the one who has to indemnify them, it means if that third party sues *them* because of your work, you have to step in and pay their legal bills and any damages. It’s a big risk, so you need to be careful not to accidentally use anything that looks like someone else's.",
      "source": "target",
