    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if i'm a designer and i accidentally use a font or an icon that i thought was free but it turns out it's copyrighted, they could basically come after me to pay for their whole legal defense? that seems like such a huge liability to carry on my own. how do people usually protect themselves from that kind of thing in these contracts?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a classic trap, and you've hit the nail right on the head. If you use a font or an icon that isn't actually free for commercial use, and someone sues the client, you're the one who gets the bill, which is a massive headache. A proper contract tries to shift that risk, or at least define the boundaries of what you're responsible for.\n\nUsually, people protect themselves by making sure the contract clearly states that *you* are responsible for ensuring everything you deliver is original or properly licensed. They might try to add clauses where you warrant that your work doesn't infringe on anyone else's rights. It’s a big piece of legal scaffolding, making sure the liability doesn't just fall onto your shoulders like a pile of wet leaves. If you don't have those protections, you're basically signing up to be the designated scapegoat when a lawsuit pops up.",
      "source": "target",
